  "scenario": "Dissolve $0.100\\,\\text{M}$ acetic acid **and** $0.100\\,\\text{M}$ sodium acetate in the same beaker. The acetate ion $\\mathrm{C_2H_3O_2^-}$ from the salt is the acid's own **conjugate base** — so the solution now holds both halves of the equilibrium $\\mathrm{HC_2H_3O_2} \\rightleftharpoons \\mathrm{H^+} + \\mathrm{C_2H_3O_2^-}$ from the start. This is a **buffer**. It is still the ICE table — the same species ledger, the same solver — but the change column starts from $[\\mathrm{C_2H_3O_2^-}]_0 = 0.100\\,\\text{M}$, not zero. That pre-loaded product is a **common ion**: by Le Chatelier it pushes the ionization left, so hardly any acid ionizes and the pH lands near $\\mathrm{p}K_a$. What is it?",
  "regimes": [
    {
      "facet": "ICE ledger (species accounting)",
      "regime": "ledger-exact"
    },
    {
      "facet": "equilibrium constant",
      "regime": "rule-sourced"
    },
    {
      "facet": "equilibrium position (buffer pH)",
      "regime": "model-exact"
    }
  ],
  "assumptions": [
    {
      "claim": "The sodium acetate dissociates completely, so $[\\mathrm{C_2H_3O_2^-}]_0 = 0.100\\,\\text{M}$ before the acid equilibrium adjusts; the $\\mathrm{Na^+}$ is a spectator.",
      "kind": "model"
    },
    {
      "claim": "This single ionization is the only reaction that matters, and activities are approximated by molar concentrations (so $K_a$ and Henderson–Hasselbalch use concentrations).",
      "kind": "model"
    },
    {
      "claim": "The $\\mathrm{H^+}$ from water's own autoionization is negligible, so $[\\mathrm{H^+}]_0 = 0$ in the table.",
      "kind": "model"
    }
  ],
